{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17623841","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17623841"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:13:25+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:13:25+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16878"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16878","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16878"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.85,0.1,0,0,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9568"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68669"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9568","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9568"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16878"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54126"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4903"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"9861"},{"type":"tags","id":"9863"},{"type":"tags","id":"9866"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22589"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22599"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68669","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/68669"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the Frank-Starling law of the heart?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Increased filling volume leads to stronger contraction","Increased afterload enhances stroke volume","Decreased calcium availability increases contractility","Sympathetic stimulation determines filling volume","Reduced heart rate increases contractile force"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EAccording to the Frank-Starling law, \u003Cstrong\u003Eincreased filling volume leads to stronger contraction \u003C/strong\u003Ein the healthy heart. When venous return increases, the ventricles fill more completely during diastole. This stretches the cardiac myocytes, optimizing the overlap between actin and myosin filaments, which results in more forceful contractions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased afterload enhances stroke volume\u003C/strong\u003E - Higher afterload actually reduces stroke volume by increasing resistance to ejection\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDecreased calcium availability increases contractility\u003C/strong\u003E - Calcium is essential for excitation-contraction coupling; reducing it impairs contractility\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESympathetic stimulation determines filling volume\u003C/strong\u003E - While autonomic input affects venous return and cardiac filling, this is not the Frank-Starling mechanism. \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReduced heart rate increases contractile force\u003C/strong\u003E - Heart rate primarily affects diastolic filling time rather than contractile force directly\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis intrinsic mechanism allows the heart to automatically match cardiac output to venous return without requiring external regulation, maintaining appropriate circulation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The Frank-Starling law states that increased ventricular filling leads to stronger cardiac contractions","Stretching of cardiac myocytes optimizes overlap between actin and myosin filaments","This mechanism allows the heart to automatically match cardiac output with venous return"],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019","Asbury, C., Rieke, F., Hille, B., Bothwell, M., \u0026 Tuthill, J. (2023) Physiology. Simple Book Publishing. https://uw.pressbooks.pub/physiology/."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54126"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16878"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54126","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/54126"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-10T09:30:37+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-10T09:47:00+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9568"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68669"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}}